<div style="position:absolute;line-height:0;border-style:solid;left:0;top:0;border-width:0 100px 200px 0;border-color:Blue"></div><div style="border:solid transparent;position:absolute;width:100px;line-height:0;right:100px; top:100px; border-width:41.437558099328px 91.0105970685px 0 0; border-top-color:purple"></div>
<div style="position:absolute;line-height:0;border-style:solid;left:0;top:0;border-width:0 200px 100px 0;border-color:purple"></div>
</div>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<p>Religion in Haiti according to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pew_Research_Center" title="Pew Research Center">Pew Research Center</a> (2010)<sup id="cite_ref-332" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-332">&#91;330&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:purple; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Catholicism (56.8%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:Blue; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Protestantism (29.6%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:gray; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Unaffiliated (10.6%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:Red; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Other (3%)</div>
</div>
</div></div>
<p>The 2017 CIA Factbook reported that around 54.7% of Haitians profess to being <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholicism_in_Haiti" class="mw-redirect" title="Roman Catholicism in Haiti">Catholics</a> while <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protestantism_in_Haiti" title="Protestantism in Haiti">Protestants</a> made up about 28.5% of the population (Baptist 15.4%, Pentecostal 7.9%, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seventh-day_Adventist" class="mw-redirect" title="Seventh-day Adventist">Seventh-day Adventist</a> 3%, Methodist 1.5%, other 0.7%). Other sources put the Protestant population higher than this, suggesting that it might have formed one-third of the population in 2001.<sup id="cite_ref-ReyStepick2013_333-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-ReyStepick2013-333">&#91;331&#93;</a></sup> Like other countries in Latin America, Haiti has witnessed a general Protestant expansion, which is largely <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evangelical_Protestant" class="mw-redirect" title="Evangelical Protestant">Evangelical</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentecostal" class="mw-redirect" title="Pentecostal">Pentecostal</a> in nature.<sup id="cite_ref-334" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-334">&#91;332&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-335" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-335">&#91;333&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-336" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-336">&#91;334&#93;</a></sup> Haitian <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_(Catholicism)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cardinal (Catholicism)">Cardinal</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chibly_Langlois" title="Chibly Langlois">Chibly Langlois</a> is president of the National Bishops Conference of the Catholic Church.
</p><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_vodou" class="mw-redirect" title="Haitian vodou">Vodou</a>, a religion with West African roots similar to those of <a href="Cuba" title="Cuba">Cuba</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brazil" title="Brazil">Brazil</a>, originated during colonial times in which slaves were obliged to disguise their <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loa" title="Loa">loa</a>, or spirits, as <a href="Catholic_Church" title="Catholic Church">Roman Catholic</a> saints, an element of a process called <a href="Syncretism" title="Syncretism">syncretism</a> and is still practiced by some Haitians today. Due to the religious syncretism between Catholicism and Vodou, it is difficult to estimate the number of Vodouists in Haiti.<sup id="cite_ref-337" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-337">&#91;335&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-338" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-338">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> The religion has historically been persecuted and misrepresented in popular media, however in 2003 the Government recognized the faith as an official religion of the nation.<sup id="cite_ref-CIA_World_Factbook_–_Haiti_18-14" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-CIA_World_Factbook_–_Haiti-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Minority religions in Haiti include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam_in_Haiti" title="Islam in Haiti">Islam</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bah%C3%A1%27%C3%AD_Faith_in_Haiti" class="mw-redirect" title="Bahá&#39;í Faith in Haiti">Bahá'í Faith</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Jews_in_Haiti" title="History of the Jews in Haiti">Judaism</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-CIA_20110303_4-2" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-CIA_20110303-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Languages">Languages</span></h3>
<p>The two official languages of Haiti are <a href="French_language" title="French language">French</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_Creole" title="Haitian Creole">Haitian Creole</a>. French is the principal written and administratively authorized language (as well as the main language of the press) and is spoken by 42% of Haitians.<sup id="cite_ref-339" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-339">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-340" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-340">&#91;338&#93;</a></sup> It is spoken by all educated Haitians, is the medium of instruction in most schools, and is used in the business sector. It is also used in ceremonial events such as weddings, graduations and church Masses. Haiti is one of two independent nations in the Americas (along with Canada) to designate French as an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Official_language" title="Official language">official language</a>; the other French-speaking areas are all <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_overseas_departments_and_territories" class="mw-redirect" title="French overseas departments and territories">overseas</a> <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Departments_of_France" title="Departments of France">départements</a></i>, or <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overseas_collectivity" title="Overseas collectivity">collectivités</a>,</i> of France.
</p><p>Haitian Creole,<sup id="cite_ref-341" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-341">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup> which has recently undergone a standardization, is spoken by virtually the entire population of Haiti.<sup id="cite_ref-342" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-342">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup> Haitian Creole is one of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French-based_creole_languages" title="French-based creole languages">French-based creole languages</a>. Its vocabulary is 90% derived from French, but its grammar resembles that of some West African languages. It also has influences from Taino, Spanish, and Portuguese.<sup id="cite_ref-343" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-343">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> Haitian Creole is related to the other <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French-based_creole_languages" title="French-based creole languages">French creoles</a>, but most closely to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antillean_Creole" title="Antillean Creole">Antillean Creole</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louisiana_Creole_French" class="mw-redirect" title="Louisiana Creole French">Louisiana Creole</a> variants.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Emigration">Emigration</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_diaspora" title="Haitian diaspora">Haitian diaspora</a></div>
<p>There is a large Haitian diaspora community, predominantly based in the US and Canada, France, and the wealthier Caribbean islands.
</p><p>Emigrants from Haiti have constituted a segment of American and Canadian society since before <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_Revolution" title="Haitian Revolution">the independence of Haiti from France</a> in 1804.<sup id="cite_ref-HammondCanadaHaiti2010_344-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-HammondCanadaHaiti2010-344">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-PBSResourceBank_345-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-PBSResourceBank-345">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> Many influential early American settlers and black freemen, including <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Baptiste_Point_du_Sable" title="Jean Baptiste Point du Sable">Jean Baptiste Point du Sable</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._E._B._Du_Bois" title="W. E. B. Du Bois">W. E. B. Du Bois</a>, were of Haitian origin.<sup id="cite_ref-Kinzie_1856_190_346-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Kinzie_1856_190-346">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Meehan_1963_445_347-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Meehan_1963_445-347">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Cohn2009_348-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Cohn2009-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Lewis18_349-0" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Lewis18-349">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Jean Baptiste Point du Sable, an immigrant from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint-Domingue" title="Saint-Domingue">Saint-Domingue</a> (now the Republic of Haiti), founded the first nonindigenous settlement in what is now <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago,_Illinois" class="mw-redirect" title="Chicago, Illinois">Chicago, Illinois</a>, the third largest city in the United States. The state of Illinois and city of Chicago declared du Sable the founder of Chicago on 26 October 1968.<sup id="cite_ref-Kinzie_1856_190_346-1" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Kinzie_1856_190-346">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Meehan_1963_445_347-1" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Meehan_1963_445-347">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Cohn2009_348-1" class="reference"><a href="Haiti#cite_note-Cohn2009-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
